Avatar:
We splitted the avatar implementation between a few classes in the package pepse.world.avatar
to split to smaller responsibilities.

Class Avatar:
This holds the real data and actions of the avatar: energy, velocity, jumping, movement,
collisions. Also reads input and turns it into an AvatarInput object. 
It doesn't decide the Avatarstate.

Class AvatarInput: 
Helper that stores left, right, and jump instead of passing input keys.

Interface AvatarState:
Interface for the avatar states. Each state has shouldEnter,
enter, update, and exit. shouldEnter tells AvatarControl when this state is the
correct one (which will make it be/not be the current state).
enter changes the animation, update handles the behavior of the avatar during that state,
this means the state could deside how the movement during it works.
The states don't switch themselfs to other states.

Classes IdleState, RunState, JumpState: 
IdleState is the default state when the avatar is on the ground and not running.
It gives the avatar 1 energy each update.

RunState is used when the avatar is on the ground, exactly one horizontal key is
pressed, and the avatar has enough energy. It moves the avatar horizontally and
spends 2 energy each update.

JumpState is used when the avatar is not on the ground. It allows horizontal
movement in the air without spending energy. It also handles double jump. A
double jump is allowed only while falling, and costs 50 energy.

Class AvatarControl:
Controls the state changes. It has a list of states ordered by
priority: jump, run, idle (if we add more states, we can just add them to the list,
at any priority wanted if it matters to us, also we can add stricked check for idle mode
if we dont want it as default). Every update it asks the states if they 
should enter, and changes to the first state that fits (later if the state doesnt change -
we just update, no exit and enter when not needed).

Class AvatarStateFactory:
Creates and stores the state objects. AvatarControl receives it and
uses the same state objects instead of creating new ones every update.

Energy:
Stored inside Avatar and is between 0 and 100.
Energy changes only through methods like trySpendEnergy and addEnergy.
trySpendEnergy checks that there is enough energy before spending it.

The energy display is implemented by EnergyCounter class, (also in the avatar
package). EnergyCounter is a GameObject in the UI layer. It shows only the energy
number, we colored it from green to red (its little and relevant only to it so we 
did the color inside the class).

EnergyCounter does not know Avatar. Instead, PepseGameManager connects them with
a callback. Avatar calls the callback only when the energy really changes, not every
update.

Trees:
We implemented the trees in the package pepse.world.trees.

Class Flora: 
Creates trees in a given x range. It uses ground height function (instead 
of receiving Terrain itself). We give it groundHeightAt as callback from terrain, 
Keeping encapsulation.
Also receives a seed and uses deterministic randomness by x coordinate, so
the same tree will be created again at the same x value.

Class Tree:
Creates the GameObjects of one tree. It creates trunk blocks, leaves, and
fruits. The trunk blocks are solid and have the tag "trunk", so the avatar can
stand on them like ground. ####how does this work? seems sus

Class Leaf:
Extends GameObject. Leaves do not collide with anything. Each leaf starts
moving after a small random delay using ScheduledTask. Then it uses two
transitions: one for changing the angle, and one for changing the dimensions.

Class Fruit:
Extends GameObject. It collides only with the avatar. When the avatar
eats a fruit, the fruit disappears, runs a callback, and then reappears after 30
seconds. The callback is passed from PepseGameManager through Flora and Tree,
and adds energy to the avatar. Doesn't know the Avatar class internals.

Additional classes: none.

API changes: none.
